    Ellipsoid with a=c minor Axis Intersection Invariant Proof Sketch

    Notebook Generated in Sage Python + Jupyter

    Also note all 3d graphs are live and can be rotated/zoomed.

    In addition, graphs are rendered low poly to speed up page loading speeds.

    Recently, I was working through some mathematics on optical polarizers, and it turns out that an ellipsoid surface whose axial intercepts(for light traveling parallel to that axis) are the refractive indeces of the dielectric under examination is useful for determining the polarizing behavior of the dielectric.

    The general equation for an ellpsoid is

    \frac {x^2} {a^2} + \frac {y^2} {b^2} + \frac {z^2} {c^2} = 1

    Say we have a dielectric whose refractive index along the z and x axis are restricted to being equal, we might get the following ellipsoid:

    x^2 + \frac {y^2} {4} + z^2 = 1
    var('x,y,z,t')
ellipsoid = x^2 + .25*y^2 + z^2 - 1==0

#plot bounds
lims = -2,2

implicit_plot3d(ellipsoid, (x,*lims), (y,*lims), (z,*lims),
                color='blue',opacity=.5, plot_points=20, axes=True)

    This ellipsoid is also called the optical indicatrix.

    In the text, Optoelectronics & Photonics: Principles & Practices (2nd Edition) section 6.2B, anisotropic materials are said to exhibit different polarization as light passes through the material from different directions.

    Also, the field of incoming light gets split into two orthogonal components which experience different refractive indeces. The two components are reffered to as the ordinary and extra-ordinary wave.

    The ordinary wave always obeys the normal refraction laws. The refractive index of the ordinary wave can be determined by intersecting a plane that passes through the origin of ellipsoid indicatrix and is normal to direction of the propagating light.

    The intersection of this plane with the ellipsoid indicatrix forms an ellipse whose minor axis is the refractive index experienced by the ordinary wave provided the ellipsoid's intercept that's not equal to the others is greater than the others(in other words, a stretched not squashed ellipsoid).

    This corresponds to a uniaxial positive crystal dielectric.

    Indicatrix with Propagating Light¶

    In the example below, we have the trivial case of light progpagating in the z^+ direction. The resulting ellipse intersection is highlighted in red and lies in the plane z=0.

    The propragating light is also represented by a red arrow.

    #plot bounds
lims = -2.5,2.5
implicit_plot3d(ellipsoid, (x,*lims), (y,*lims), (z,*lims), #ellipse
                color='blue',opacity=.5,plot_points=20) +\
implicit_plot3d(z == 0, (x,*lims), (y,*lims), (z,*lims), #plane
                color='yellow',opacity=.5,plot_points=20) +\
parametric_plot3d((cos(x), 2*sin(x), 0), (x,-pi,pi), #intersection
                  color='red') +\
arrow((0,0,0),(0,0,2),color='red')

    The text also notes that if you have two axes with equivalent indeces of refraction, say a=c and a \neq b as is the case above, then the ellipse formed by intersection with a plane passing through the origin will always have a minor axis of a provided that b > a.

    In the example above, we have a=c=1. It easy easy to see that the ellipse intersection highlighted in red also has a minor axis of length one.

    It is far more difficult to verify that this is true for arbitrary directions such as the intersection shown below.

    #plot bounds
lims = -2.5,2.5
implicit_plot3d(ellipsoid, (x,*lims), (y,*lims), (z,*lims), #ellipse
                color='blue',opacity=.5,plot_points=20) +\
implicit_plot3d(x + y + z == 0, (x,*lims), (y,*lims), (z,*lims), #plane
                color='yellow',opacity=.5,plot_points=20) +\
arrow((0,0,0),(2,2,2),color='red')

    Analytically Solving for Intersection With Affine Transformations¶

    Notice that I did not plot the intersection for the case above, this is because we have yet to find the resulting intersection.

    How would we go about analytically determining the intersection for the case above?

    An ellipsoid is essentially a streched sphere. We know that any plane-sphere intersection always forms a circle.

    What we can do is find the intersection of the yellow plane above with a unit sphere, and then apply an affine stretch to the plane and unit sphere such that the sphere becomes our original ellipsoid.

    #plot bounds
lims = -2.5,2.5
implicit_plot3d(x^2 + y^2 + z^2 == 1, (x,*lims), (y,*lims), (z,*lims), #ellipse
                color='orange',plot_points=20) +\
implicit_plot3d(ellipsoid, (x,*lims), (y,*lims), (z,*lims), #ellipse
                color='blue',opacity=.5,plot_points=20) +\
implicit_plot3d(x + y + z == 0, (x,*lims), (y,*lims), (z,*lims), #plane
                color='yellow',opacity=.9,plot_points=20) +\
arrow((0,0,0),(2,2,2),color='red')

    Intersection of Plane Through Origin of Sphere¶

    So we define our plane of intersection as \hat{n} \cdot \vec{p} = 0 where

    \vec{n} = \begin{align} \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} \end{align}

    and \hat{n} = |n|.

    \vec{p} is any point that lines on the plane.

    You can imagine that we're squeezing the ellipsoid into a sphere, that's why n_x = 2.

    We can describe the plane of intersection with a basis of two linearly independent vectors, \langle \vec{v_1}, \vec{v_2} \rangle.

    Since our plane, x + y + z = 0 and the plane z = 0 intersect, we can restrict one of our basis vectors, say \vec{v_1} to lie in the plane z=0.

    These conditions can summarized as follows:

    \hat{n} \cdot \vec{v_1} = 0
    \hat{n} \cdot \vec{v_2} = 0
    \vec{v_1} \cdot \vec{v_2} = 0
    \vec{v_1} \cdot \hat{z} = 0

    We can solve for v_1 by finding a vector that lies on the intersection of the planes x + y + z = 0 and z = 0.

    \vec{v_1} = | \hat{z} \times \hat{n} |
    from sympy import Matrix, MatrixSymbol
from sympy.physics.vector import ReferenceFrame

    r = ReferenceFrame('R')

    n = (r.x + 2*r.y + r.z).normalize()
z_hat = r.z
v1 = z_hat.cross(n).normalize()
v1_m = v1.to_matrix(r)
v1_m

    \displaystyle \left[\begin{matrix}- \frac{2 \sqrt{5}}{5}\\\frac{\sqrt{5}}{5}\\0\end{matrix}\right]

    And now to find \vec{v_2}

    \vec{v_2} = | \hat{n} \times \vec{v_1} |
    v2 = n.cross(v1).normalize()
v2_m = v2.to_matrix(r)
v2_m

    \displaystyle \left[\begin{matrix}- \frac{\sqrt{30}}{30}\\- \frac{\sqrt{30}}{15}\\\frac{\sqrt{30}}{6}\end{matrix}\right]

    Basis vectors \vec{v_1} and \vec{v_2} on the plane and in the sphere

    #plot bounds
lims = -2.5,2.5
implicit_plot3d(x^2 + y^2 + z^2 == 1, (x,*lims), (y,*lims), (z,*lims), #ellipse
                color='orange',opacity=.5,plot_points=20) +\
implicit_plot3d(x + 2*y + z == 0, (x,*lims), (y,*lims), (z,*lims), #plane
                color='yellow',opacity=.9,plot_points=20) +\
arrow((0,0,0),tuple(v1_m),color='red') +\
arrow((0,0,0),tuple(v2_m),color='blue')

    The intersection between the sphere and the plane can be parameterized as \vec{v_1} \cos(t) + \vec{v_2} \sin(t) on [ -\pi, \pi] as plotted below in red.

    #plot bounds
lims = -2.5,2.5
implicit_plot3d(x^2 + y^2 + z^2 == 1, (x,*lims), (y,*lims), (z,*lims), #sphere
                color='orange',opacity=.3,plot_points=20) +\
implicit_plot3d(x + 2*y + z == 0, (x,*lims), (y,*lims), (z,*lims), #plane
                color='yellow',opacity=.9,plot_points=20) +\
parametric_plot3d(tuple(v1_m*cos(t)+v2_m*sin(t)), (t,-pi,pi), #intersection
                  color='red',thickness=4) +\
arrow((0,0,0),tuple(v1_m),color='red') +\
arrow((0,0,0),tuple(v2_m),color='blue')

    Applying the Affine Transformation¶

    Now, lets go ahead and apply the affine stretch by a factor of two on y for everything in our space.

    This includes the sphere(which becomes an ellipsoid) as well as the basis vectors with which we plotted the intersection.

    v1_mp = v1_m.multiply_elementwise(Matrix([[1],[2],[1]]))
v2_mp = v2_m.multiply_elementwise(Matrix([[1],[2],[1]]))

    The intersection is highlighted in red below.

    Rotate the graph around to see the intersection in its fullness.

    Also, the new basis vectors have been scaled out by a factor of 2 each for visibility. Notice how the vectors are no longer orthogonal.

    #plot bounds
lims = -2.5,2.5
implicit_plot3d(ellipsoid, (x,*lims), (y,*lims), (z,*lims), #ellipsoid
                plot_points=20) +\
implicit_plot3d(x + y + z == 0, (x,*lims), (y,*lims), (z,*lims), #plane
                color='yellow',opacity=.3,plot_points=20) +\
parametric_plot3d(tuple(v1_mp*cos(t)+v2_mp*sin(t)), (t,-pi,pi), #intersection
                  color='red',thickness=10) +\
arrow((0,0,0),tuple(2*v1_mp),color='red') +\
arrow((0,0,0),tuple(2*v2_mp),color='blue')

    Graphical Confirmation Ellipse Intersection has a Minor Axis of Length a=c=1¶

    Let us see if we can inscribe a circle with radius a=c=1 inside the ellipse intersection.

    If we can, this means that the ellipse has a minor axis of length a.

    I won't go over the details on how I parameterize the inscribed circle, it should be possible to figure this our from previous exercises in this post.

    #new v1
n_c = (r.x + r.y + r.z).normalize()
z_hat_c = r.z
v1_c = z_hat_c.cross(n_c).normalize()
v1_m_c = v1_c.to_matrix(r)
v1_m_c

    \displaystyle \left[\begin{matrix}- \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\\\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\\0\end{matrix}\right]

    #new v2
v2_c = n_c.cross(v1_c).normalize()
v2_m_c = v2_c.to_matrix(r)
v2_m_c

    \displaystyle \left[\begin{matrix}- \frac{\sqrt{6}}{6}\\- \frac{\sqrt{6}}{6}\\\frac{\sqrt{6}}{3}\end{matrix}\right]

    The plot below makes it quite clear the ellipse has a minor axis of a=c=1.

    Analytically verifying that this is the case is a little more challenging...

    #plot bounds
lims = -2.5,2.5
implicit_plot3d(ellipsoid, (x,*lims), (y,*lims), (z,*lims), #ellipsoid
                opacity=.3,plot_points=20) +\
implicit_plot3d(x + y + z == 0, (x,*lims), (y,*lims), (z,*lims), #plane
                color='yellow',opacity=.3,plot_points=20) +\
parametric_plot3d(tuple(v1_mp*cos(t)+v2_mp*sin(t)), (t,-pi,pi), #intersection
                  color='red',thickness=2) +\
parametric_plot3d(tuple(v1_m_c*cos(t)+v2_m_c*sin(t)), (t,-pi,pi), #inscribed circle
                  color='red',thickness=2) +\
arrow((0,0,0),tuple(2*v1_m_c),color='red') +\
arrow((0,0,0),tuple(2*v2_m_c),color='blue')

    Analytical Verification Ellipse Intersection has a Minor Axis of Length a=c=1¶

    This is actually quite involved, I will have to come back to this...

    I do however know what a sketch for a proof would look like - see next section...

    Sketch for Proof¶

    Given an ellipsoid of the form $ \frac {x^2} {a^2} + \frac {y^2} {b^2} + \frac {z^2} {c^2} = 1$ centered about the origin that has two equal intercepts of value a=c, we want to prove that any plane slicing this ellipsoid through the origin forms an intersection ellipse whose minor axis is always of length a, provided b > a.

    One thing to notice is that if you restrain two of the intercepts of an ellipsoid to be equal, you've essentially got a sphere that's been stretched in only one direction.

    Sphere Stretched by a Factor Greater Than One: b > a¶

    In this case, the resulting ellipsoid always contains a sphere inside it. It is simple to show that a plane-sphere intersection is always a circle.

    So anytime the plane intersects with the specified ellipsoid, it also intersects with the interior sphere.

    Since it is possible to create any ellipsoid from an affine transformation on a sphere, it is possible to affinely transform any sphere-plane intersection into a ellipsoid-plane intersection.

    Since in this case, we only restrict our transformations to stretches by a factor greater than one, the ellipse resulting from the ellipsoid-plane intersection will always contain the inscribed circle from the sphere-plane intersection.

    Since we only appy one affine transformation on one axis in our space, this implies it is possible to transform the circle into the ellipse by strecthing the circle only along one of its axes(we can think of a circle as an ellipse with equal major and minor axes). This means the circle and the ellipse share an axis of the same length. Since we stretched by a factor greater than one, the shared becomes the ellipse's minor axis.

    See the sphere inscribed in the ellipsoid and the corresponding circle inscribed in the ellipse in the figure below.

    #plot bounds
lims = -2.5,2.5
implicit_plot3d(x^2 + y^2 + z^2 == 1, (x,*lims), (y,*lims), (z,*lims), #sphere
                color='orange',plot_points=20) +\
implicit_plot3d(ellipsoid, (x,*lims), (y,*lims), (z,*lims), #ellipsoid
                opacity=.3,plot_points=20) +\
implicit_plot3d(x + y + z == 0, (x,*lims), (y,*lims), (z,*lims), #plane
                color='yellow',opacity=.3,plot_points=20) +\
parametric_plot3d(tuple(v1_mp*cos(t)+v2_mp*sin(t)), (t,-pi,pi), #intersection
                  color='red',thickness=2) +\
parametric_plot3d(tuple(v1_m_c*cos(t)+v2_m_c*sin(t)), (t,-pi,pi), #inscribed circle
                  color='red',thickness=10)

    Sphere Stretched by a Factor Less Than One¶

    Similar logic applies in this case except now, the resulting ellipse is inscribed inside the circle.

    I believe this case corresponds to a uniaxial negative crystal dielectric.
